# Railway Deployment\line
\line
This project is set up for a single-host Railway deployment.\line
\line
## Service setup\line
\line
- Use the repository root as the service root.\line
- Railway config is in [railway.json](/c:/Users/peter/Projects/VSCODE/SnapQueue/SnapQueue/railway.json).\line
- The root [package.json](/c:/Users/peter/Projects/VSCODE/SnapQueue/SnapQueue/package.json) exists only to make Railway detect this repository as a Node app and run the deployment scripts from the repo root.\line
- The frontend is built first, then copied into `backend/client-dist`, and the backend serves both the website and the API from one service.\line
\line
## Required environment variables\line
\line
Add these in Railway:\line
\line
```env\line
NODE_ENV=production\line
MONGO_URI=your-mongodb-connection-string\line
JWT_SECRET=your-random-secret\line
\line
BREVO_API_KEY=your-brevo-key\line
MAIL_FROM=your-sender-email\line
CONTACT_RECEIVER_EMAIL=where-contact-form-messages-go\line
\line
CLOUDINARY_CLOUD_NAME=your-cloud-name\line
CLOUDINARY_API_KEY=your-api-key\line
CLOUDINARY_API_SECRET=your-api-secret\line
\line
GEMINI_API_KEY=your-gemini-key\line
GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID=your-google-oauth-client-id\line
```\line
\line
Use [backend/.env.example](/c:/Users/peter/Projects/VSCODE/SnapQueue/SnapQueue/backend/.env.example) as the reference list, then copy the values you need into Railway Variables or your local `backend/.env`.\line
\line
## Recommended public URL variables\line
\line
Set these to the same Railway app URL:\line
\line
```env\line
CLIENT_URL=https://your-app.up.railway.app\line
FRONTEND_URL=https://your-app.up.railway.app\line
BACKEND_URL=https://your-app.up.railway.app\line
PUBLIC_URL=https://your-app.up.railway.app\line
APP_URL=https://your-app.up.railway.app\line
PASSWORD_RESET_BASE_URL=https://your-app.up.railway.app\line
```\line
\line
## Frontend variables\line
\line
For single-host Railway:\line
\line
- Leave `VITE_API_URL` unset.\line
- `VITE_BOOTSTRAP_MIN_MS` and `VITE_BOOTSTRAP_MAX_MS` are optional.\line
- `VITE_GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID` is only needed if you want the frontend build to read it directly. The backend already reads `GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID`.\line
\line
## Notes\line
\line
- `PORT` is provided by Railway automatically.\line
- Do not deploy only the `frontend` folder.\line
- If Google login is enabled, make sure the Railway domain is added to your Google OAuth allowed origins and redirect settings.\line
